The asymmetry reflects a fundamental difference in what each check actually measures and whether that measurement is meaningful in an unsigned debug build.

`SystemVMDetector.detect()` and `SysctlDebuggerAttachmentDetector.detect()` both short-circuit in DEBUG:

```swift
// VMDetector.swift
func detect() -> VMDetectionResult {
    #if DEBUG
    return .notVirtual
    #else
    return detectWithoutDevelopmentBypass()
    #endif
}

// DebuggerAttachmentDetector.swift
func detect() -> DebuggerAttachmentDetectionResult {
    #if DEBUG
    return .notDetectedForDevelopment
    #else
    return detectWithoutDevelopmentBypass()
    #endif
}
```

But both expose `detectWithoutDevelopmentBypass()` so unit tests running in DEBUG can exercise the real detection logic — the IOKit/hardware model checks, MAC address prefix matching, and `kinfo_proc.kp_proc.p_flag & P_TRACED` sysctl query — without those checks interfering with normal Xcode development.

`SecurityFrameworkRuntimeCodeSignatureVerifier.verify()` also short-circuits in DEBUG, but has no equivalent bypass method. The reason: its release path calls `SecCodeCopySelf`, compiles a requirement string pinned to `LicenseSensitiveConstants.runtimePinnedTeamIdentifier` and `LicenseSensitiveConstants.runtimePinnedLeafCommonName` via `SecRequirementCreateWithString`, then validates with `SecCodeCheckValidityWithErrors`. An app built from Xcode without a Developer ID certificate will always fail this check — not because of a logic bug, but because the certificate doesn't exist in the build. A `detectWithoutDevelopmentBypass()` equivalent would deterministically fail every time in a test environment and provide no useful signal.

The VM and debugger checks test observable OS state that is meaningful regardless of signing configuration. The code signing check tests a property (the certificate chain) that is inseparable from the production build environment. The bypass method exists exactly where the underlying logic has value independent of signing state, and is absent where it does not.

